464":"circa 1464","1476":"1476","1443":"1443","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","about 1464":"circa 1464","about 1442":"circa 1442","about 1443":"circa 1443","1418":"1418","Überlingen, Baden, Germany":"Bezirksamt Überlingen, Baden, Duitsland","Deutschland":"Duitsland","Schaffhausen, Schweiz":"Schaffhausen, Zwitserland","Überlingen, Bodenseekreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Überlingen, Bodenseekreis, Baden-Württemberg, Duitsland"},"en":{"about 1443–":"about 1443–Deceased","1443–Female":"1443–Deceased","1440–1476":"1440–1476","1464–1512":"1464–1512","–Female":"Deceased","1418–Male":"1418–Deceased","1512":"1512","environ 1464":"about 1464","1476":"1476","1443":"1443","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","about 1464":"about 1464","about 1442":"about 1442","about 1443":"about 1443","1418":"1418","Überlingen, Baden, Germany":"Bezirksamt Überlingen, Baden, Germany","Deutschland":"Germany","Schaffhausen, Schweiz":"Schaffhausen, Switzerland","Überlingen, Bodenseekreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Überlingen, Bodenseekreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Schweigker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Matthias.","German: variant of   Schweickert  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Schweickert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ewald, Hans.","German (mainly Württemberg and Bavaria): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>swinth</i> ‘strong, fast’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’; the <i>-t</i> is epenthetic."]}]},{"name":"Margaretha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaretha Schweigker was born about 1443, in Bezirksamt Überlingen, Baden, Ger